\subsection{init\_disk\_iob (\$6C2E)}

Sets the zero-page pointer [[\$08/\$09]] to the RWTS Input/Output Block
at [[\$B7E8]].  Called once during [[GAME\_INIT]].  The game's disk I/O
routines (relocated to \$B300--\$BFFF during [[game\_init]]) use this
pointer to access the IOB fields via indirect-indexed addressing:
e.g.\ [[STA (\$08),Y]] with [[Y]] selecting the field (track, sector,
command code, buffer address, etc.).  The RWTS entry point is at [[\$B7B5]].

<<zero page defines>>=
RWTS_IOB_PTR            EQU     $08     ; ZP pointer to RWTS IOB ($B7E8)
@ %def RWTS_IOB_PTR

<<defines>>=
RWTS_IOB                EQU     $B7E8   ; RWTS Input/Output Block (14 bytes)
@ %def RWTS_IOB

\subsection{init\_stub2 (\$6B94)}

A single [[RTS]]---another no-op stub called from [[GAME\_INIT]], like
[[INIT\_STUB]] at [[\$7919]].

<<init stub2>>=
    ORG     $6B94
INIT_STUB2:
    RTS
@ %def INIT_STUB2

<<init disk iob>>=
    ORG     $6C2E
INIT_DISK_IOB:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #>RWTS_IOB              ; \ set RWTS IOB pointer
    LDY     #<RWTS_IOB              ;  | $08/$09 = $B7E8
    STA     RWTS_IOB_PTR+1          ;  |
    STY     RWTS_IOB_PTR            ; /
    RTS
@ %def INIT_DISK_IOB

\label{sec:scene_loop}

This is the main scene display loop.  It is called with the scene number
in~A.

<<scene loop>>=
    ORG     $6C37
SCENE_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     SCENE_NUMBER            ; store scene number
    LDA     #$14
    STA     BLINK_COL               ; disable blink cursor

    JSR     SAVE_ZP_POINTERS

    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; PRNG output
    AND     #$0A                    ; test bits 1 and 3
    BNE     .display                ; if any set, skip disk load
    JSR     LOAD_SCENE_DATA

.display:
    JSR     $A478                   ; keyboard/timing check (EALDR resident)
    BCS     .exit                   ; carry set = user pressed key

    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR
    STOW    SCENE_TEXT_DATA,TEXT_STREAM_PTR ; scene text data → $06/$07
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER

    LDX     #$06                    ; script index 6
    JSR     SCRIPT_ENGINE           ; run script #3 ($A300)
    LDA     SCENE_TRANSITION        ; scene transition flag
    BEQ     .done                   ; zero = no transition
    STA     SCENE_NUMBER            ; set new scene number
    JMP     .display                ; continue

.exit:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #$1B
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE         ; display message (mode off)
                                    ; fall through to .done

.done:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #$00                    ; \
    STA     LOCATION_POS           ;  | clear location flags
    STA     LOCATION_STYLE          ; /
    JSR     ENTER_LOCATION          ; redraw map if location changed
    JMP     RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS     ; restore and return
@ %def SCENE_LOOP

The scene loop calls [[$A478]] (a resident routine from EALDR, still in
memory at [[$A000]]--[[$BFFF]]) each iteration to check for user input.
If carry is set (key pressed), the loop exits.  Otherwise, it displays
the status bar, renders the scene text from [[$5C00]], runs script \#3
(the attract animation at [[$A300]]), and checks [[$5CFF]] for a scene
transition.

The [[$5C00]] region is populated dynamically by [[LOAD\_SCENE\_DATA]]
from disk.  Its contents change with each scene.

\section{Utility routines}

\subsection{save\_zp\_pointers / restore\_zp\_pointers}

These routines save and restore four zero-page pointer pairs to/from
fixed addresses in the [[$5A00]] page.  The pointers are used throughout
the game for character records, text buffers, and cursor state.

<<defines>>=
SAVED_BC            EQU     $5A9A   ; saved TARGET_REC/PRINT_STRING_ADDR (2 bytes)
SAVED_F8            EQU     $5A9C   ; saved ENTITY_PTR pointer (2 bytes)
SAVED_BE            EQU     $5A9E   ; saved CHAR_REC/ENTITY_REC (2 bytes)
SAVED_F4            EQU     $5AA0   ; saved MOB_PTR pointer (2 bytes)
@ %def SAVED_BC SAVED_F8 SAVED_BE SAVED_F4

<<save zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D53
SAVE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     TARGET_REC
    STA     SAVED_BC
    LDA     TARGET_REC+1
    STA     SAVED_BC+1
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR
    STA     SAVED_F8
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR+1
    STA     SAVED_F8+1
    LDA     DATA_PTR
    STA     SAVED_BE
    LDA     DATA_PTR+1
    STA     SAVED_BE+1
    LDA     MOB_PTR
    STA     SAVED_F4
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    STA     SAVED_F4+1
    RTS
@ %def SAVE_ZP_POINTERS
@

<<restore zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D7C
RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     SAVED_BC
    STA     TARGET_REC
    LDA     SAVED_BC+1
    STA     TARGET_REC+1
    LDA     SAVED_F8
    STA     ENTITY_PTR
    LDA     SAVED_F8+1
    STA     ENTITY_PTR+1
    LDA     SAVED_BE
    STA     DATA_PTR
    LDA     SAVED_BE+1
    STA     DATA_PTR+1
    LDA     SAVED_F4
    STA     MOB_PTR
    LDA     SAVED_F4+1
    STA     MOB_PTR+1
    RTS
@ %def RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS

\subsection{relocate\_hires\_staging (\$6DA5)}

During startup, tracks [[\$0F]] and [[\$10]] are loaded into the hi-res
page area [[$2000--$3FFF]] as a staging area.  This routine, called from
[[game\_init]], copies the staged data to its runtime addresses and clears
the hi-res page:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Source} & \thead{Destination} & \thead{Size} \\
\midrule
\$2000--\$32FF & \$9600--\$A8FF & 19 pages (HRCG code + standard font) \\
\$3300--\$3FFF & \$B300--\$BFFF & 13 pages (disk I/O routines) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The copy loop at [[.copy]] also clears each source byte, leaving the
hi-res page zeroed for use as a graphics buffer.

<<relocate hires staging>>=
    ORG     $6DA5
RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$00
    STA     COPY_DEST                         ; \  dest = $9600
    STA     COPY_SRC                         ; \  src  = $2000
    LDA     #$20                        ;  |
    STA     COPY_SRC+1                         ; /  src hi
    LDA     #$96                        ;  |
    STA     COPY_DEST+1                         ; /  dest hi
    LDY     #$00
    LDX     #$13                        ; 19 pages: $2000-$32FF -> $9600-$A8FF
    JSR     .copy
    LDX     #$0D                        ; 13 pages: $3300-$3FFF -> $B300-$BFFF
    LDA     #$B3
    STA     COPY_DEST+1                         ; dest hi = $B3
    INC     COPY_SRC+1                         ; src hi = $33 (was $32 after first pass)

.copy:
    LDA     (COPY_SRC),Y                     ; load from source
    STA     (COPY_DEST),Y                     ; store to dest
    LDA     #$00
    STA     (COPY_SRC),Y                     ; clear source byte
    DEY
    BNE     .copy                       ; inner loop (256 bytes)
    DEX
    BNE     .next_page                  ; more pages?
    RTS

.next_page:
    INC     COPY_SRC+1                         ; next source page
    INC     COPY_DEST+1                         ; next dest page
    JMP     .copy
@ %def RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING

\subsection{step\_prng (\$78A8)}

The pseudo-random number generator computes:
$$\texttt{val}_{n+1} = 69 \cdot \texttt{val}_n + \$53 \pmod{256}$$
and stores both the full result and a shifted copy.

<<step prng>>=
    ORG     $78A8
STEP_PRNG:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     PRNG_STATE              ; val
    ASL                       ; val*2
    ASL                       ; val*4
    STA     PRNG_TEMP               ; temp = val*4
    ASL                       ; val*8
    ASL                       ; val*16
    ASL                       ; val*32
    ASL                       ; val*64
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_TEMP               ; val*64 + val*4 = val*68
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_STATE              ; val*68 + val = val*69
    CLC
    ADC     #$53                    ; + $53
    STA     PRNG_STATE              ; store full result
    LSR                             ; val >> 1
    STA     PRNG_OUTPUT             ; shifted copy (used for random tests)
    RTS
@ %def STEP_PRNG

Two shifts produce [[val*4]], saved to [[PRNG\_TEMP]].  Four more shifts give
[[val*64]].  Adding [[val*4]] gives [[val*68]], then adding [[val]] gives
[[val*69]].  Adding [[\$53]] completes the LCG step.  This is a linear
congruential generator with multiplier 69, increment \$53, and modulus 256.

\subsection{random\_in\_range (\$1317)}

Returns a uniform random integer in [[0..A$-$1]] using rejection sampling.
The routine finds the smallest bitmask that covers the range, then repeatedly
calls [[STEP\_PRNG]] and masks [[PRNG\_OUTPUT]] until the result is less than
or equal to the shifted limit.  This avoids modulo bias.

Input: A~=~range limit (1--127).  If A~=~0, returns~0 immediately.
Output: A~=~random value in [[0..limit$-$1]].

<<defines>>=
RNG_LIMIT           EQU     $5A11   ; random\_in\_range temporary (limit/shift count)
RNG_MASK            EQU     $5A12   ; random\_in\_range bit mask
@ %def RNG_LIMIT RNG_MASK

<<random in range>>=
    ORG     $1317
RANDOM_IN_RANGE:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     RNG_LIMIT               ; save range limit
    CMP     #$00
    BNE     .nonzero
    RTS                             ; range=0 → return 0

.nonzero:
    CMP     #$02                    ; \
    BPL     .ge2                    ;  |
    LDY     #$06                    ;  | range 1: mask=$40, shift=6
    LDA     #$40                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge2:
    CMP     #$04                    ; \
    BPL     .ge4                    ;  |
    LDY     #$05                    ;  | range 2-3: mask=$60, shift=5
    LDA     #$60                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge4:
    CMP     #$08                    ; \
    BPL     .ge8                    ;  |
    LDY     #$04                    ;  | range 4-7: mask=$70, shift=4
    LDA     #$70                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge8:
    CMP     #$10                    ; \
    BPL     .ge16                   ;  |
    LDY     #$03                    ;  | range 8-15: mask=$78, shift=3
    LDA     #$78                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge16:
    CMP     #$20                    ; \
    BPL     .ge32                   ;  |
    LDY     #$02                    ;  | range 16-31: mask=$7C, shift=2
    LDA     #$7C                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge32:
    CMP     #$40                    ; \
    BPL     .ge64                   ;  |
    LDY     #$01                    ;  | range 32-63: mask=$7E, shift=1
    LDA     #$7E                    ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask              ; /
.ge64:
    LDY     #$00                    ; range 64-127: mask=$7F, shift=0
    LDA     #$7F

.have_mask:
    STA     RNG_MASK                ; save bit mask
    LDA     RNG_LIMIT               ; reload range limit
    STY     RNG_LIMIT               ; save shift count in RNG_LIMIT
.shift_loop:
    DEY                             ; \
    BMI     .shifted                ;  | shift limit left by (shift count)
    CLC                             ;  | positions so it aligns with the
    ROL                       ;  | mask bits
    BNE     .shift_loop             ; /
.shifted:
    LDY     RNG_LIMIT               ; Y = shift count
    STA     RNG_LIMIT               ; save shifted limit

.sample:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG               ; get next random byte
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    AND     RNG_MASK                ; mask to relevant bits
    CMP     RNG_LIMIT               ; compare with shifted limit
    BEQ     .accept                 ; equal → accept
    BPL     .sample                 ; greater → reject, retry

.accept:
    DEY                             ; \
    BPL     .shift_right            ;  | shift result right by (shift count)
    RTS                             ;  | to recover the final value
.shift_right:
    CLC                             ;  |
    ROR                       ;  |
    BCC     .accept                 ; / (always taken: masked bit is 0)
@ %def RANDOM_IN_RANGE

\subsection{first/next\_group\_member (\$12FA/\$1300)}

Group iteration uses two zero-page pointer pairs: [[\$FA/\$FB]] points
to the group head (or the member currently being processed), and
[[MOB\_PTR]] is the iteration cursor that advances through the chain.
Both routines follow the ``next'' link in byte~2 of a mob data record,
resolve it via [[GET\_MOB\_DATA]], and store the result in~[[MOB\_PTR]].
If the link is zero (end of chain), [[MOB\_PTR]] is set to null.

\begin{itemize}
\item [[\$12FA]] ([[FIRST\_GROUP\_MEMBER]]): begins iteration by following
      byte~2 of the group head at~[[\$FA/\$FB]].  If that link is zero,
      falls through to check [[MOB\_PTR]] as a fallback.
\item [[\$1300]] ([[NEXT\_GROUP\_MEMBER]]): continues iteration by following
      byte~2 of the current cursor at~[[MOB\_PTR]].
\end{itemize}

<<advance group link>>=
    ORG     $12FA
FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$02                    ; \
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y                 ;  | check byte 2 of group head ($FA)
    BNE     .resolve                ; /  if nonzero, follow it
NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER:
    LDY     #$02                    ; \
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ;  | check byte 2 of cursor ($F4)
    BNE     .resolve                ; /  if nonzero, follow it
    STA     MOB_PTR                     ; \  end of chain:
    STA     MOB_PTR+1                     ; /  null out MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1
    RTS
.resolve:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA            ; resolve link -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR                     ; \
    STA     MOB_PTR                     ;  | MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1                     ;  | (advance cursor to next record)
    STA     MOB_PTR+1                     ; /
    RTS
@ %def FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER

\subsection{clamp\_char\_field (\$0A93)}

Ensures that byte~6 of the character record at [[MOB_PTR]] has its lower 6~bits
at least as large as byte~5's lower 5~bits.  If byte~6 is smaller, its low
bits are replaced with byte~5's value (preserving byte~6's top 2~bits).
This clamps a stat floor---likely ensuring current HP does not fall below
a minimum derived from another field.

<<clamp char field>>=
    ORG     $0A93
CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 5 of record
    AND     #$1F                    ; low 5 bits = minimum
    STA     $BA
    INY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 6 of record
    AND     #$3F                    ; low 6 bits = current value
    CMP     $BA
    BCC     .clamp                  ; current < minimum → clamp
    RTS                             ; current >= minimum → done
.clamp:
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; reload byte 6
    AND     #$C0                    ; preserve top 2 bits
    ORA     $BA                     ; set low bits to minimum
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD

\subsection{draw\_char\_at\_pos (\$1156)}

Given a map position in~A, sets the font cursor to the corresponding
column and row, looks up what character or mob occupies that position,
determines its font character, and draws it.

<<draw char at pos>>=
    ORG     $1156
DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW           ; A=pos → A=col, Y=row
    STA     FONT_COL                ; set font column
    STY     FONT_ROW                ; set font row
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS           ; re-linearize (A = col + row*20)
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS      ; look up entity at position → ENTITY_REC
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR     ; determine font char from entity data
    JMP     RENDER_FONT_CHAR        ; render the font character
@ %def DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS

\subsection{display\_status\_bar (\$6D1F)}

Draws the ``PRESS SPACE BAR TO CONTINUE'' (or ``PRESS THE BUTTON TO
CONTINUE'') message in the text window at the bottom of the screen.

<<display status bar>>=
    ORG     $6D1F
DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$90                    ; ctrl-P with high bit (toggle inverse)
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    STOW    STATUS_BORDER_DATA,TEXT_STREAM_PTR ; status bar border data → $06/$07
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER           ; draw border box
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB           ; Ctrl-A, '0'
    LDA     #$17
    STA     TEXT_ROW                ; WNDBTM = 23

    LDA     $5A00                   ; joystick/keyboard flag
    BNE     .joystick

    ; Keyboard path:
    LDA     #<S_PRESS_SPACE
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     #>S_PRESS_SPACE
.store_hi_and_print:
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
.set_margin:
    LDA     #$04
    STA     TEXT_COL                ; WNDLFT = 4
    JMP     PRINT_FROM_PTR         ; print string, return

.joystick:
    LDA     #<S_PRESS_BUTTON
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     #>S_PRESS_BUTTON
    JMP     .store_hi_and_print     ; reuse STA PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1 from keyboard path
@ %def DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR

The border box data at [[STATUS\_BORDER\_DATA]] is drawn via the hi-res
text renderer.  The prompt text is printed via [[PRINT\_FROM\_PTR]].

\subsection{print\_from\_ptr (\$775C)}

Prints a length-prefixed string from [[PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]] via COUT:

<<print from ptr>>=
    ORG     $775C
PRINT_FROM_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y                 ; first byte = length
    TAX
.loop:
    DEX
    BPL     .next
    RTS                             ; done

.next:
    INY
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y                 ; read next char
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    JMP     .loop
@ %def PRINT_FROM_PTR

\subsection{display\_message (\$761E)}

Displays a message from the game's message table.  Takes the message
index in~A.  The message table base address is stored at
[[\$4005/\$4006]]; each entry is a length-prefixed string.  The routine
walks the table to find the Xth entry, then displays up to three lines
in the status window.

For the first line ([[MSG\_LINE\_COUNT]]~=~0), it calls
[[PRINT\_BOTTOM\_CENTERED]] then scrolls.  For the second line
([[MSG\_LINE\_COUNT]]~=~1), it scrolls first, then prints.  For the
third and subsequent lines, it scrolls, prints, then calls [[\$0D10]]
(delay) and [[\$774E]] ([[PRINT\_CTRL\_AB]]) before looping back.

An entry with a zero length byte terminates the message.  If exactly
two lines were printed, a final scroll is performed on exit.

<<defines>>=
MSG_TABLE_PTR           EQU     $4005   ; message table base (2 bytes)
MSG_LINE_COUNT          EQU     $5A57   ; lines printed so far
@ %def MSG_TABLE_PTR MSG_LINE_COUNT

<<display message>>=
    ORG     $761E
DISPLAY_MESSAGE:
    SUBROUTINE

    TAX                             ; X = message index
    LDA     MSG_TABLE_PTR           ; load table base into PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     MSG_TABLE_PTR+1
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    LDA     #$00
    STA     MSG_LINE_COUNT          ; reset line counter

    JMP     .check_index            ; skip to index check

.skip_entry:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; get string length
    TAY
    SEC                             ; +1 for length byte itself
    ADC     PRINT_STRING_ADDR       ; advance pointer past this entry
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    CPY     #$00                    ; was length zero? (end of table)
    BNE     .skip_entry             ; no — keep skipping within group
.next_index:
    DEX
.check_index:
    CPX     #$00
    BNE     .skip_entry             ; more entries to skip

DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP:
.print_loop:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; get length of current string
    BNE     .has_text               ; nonzero — print it

    ; length is zero — message is done
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    CMP     #$02                    ; printed exactly 2 lines?
    BEQ     .final_scroll
    RTS                             ; otherwise just return
.final_scroll:
    JMP     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll once more and return

.has_text:
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    CMP     #$01
    BMI     .first_line             ; line_count < 1: first line
    BEQ     .second_line            ; line_count == 1: second line

    ; third+ line: scroll, then print
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll status window
.second_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED   ; print centered on row 23
    JMP     .advance

.first_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED   ; print centered on row 23
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE                   ; scroll status window

.advance:
    INC     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    SEC
    ADC     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; add length + 1 (SEC sets carry)
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    LDA     #$01
    CMP     MSG_LINE_COUNT          ; printed <= 1 lines?
    BCC     .pause                  ; no — need to pause
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y   ; peek at next entry
    BNE     .print_loop             ; more text — keep printing

.pause:
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION    ; delay
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB           ; reset character set
    JMP     .print_loop             ; continue with next line
@ %def DISPLAY_MESSAGE DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP

\subsection{print\_ctrl\_AB (\$774E)}

Sends Ctrl-A and [['0']] to COUT (selects character set~0 in the HRCG):

<<print ctrl ab>>=
    ORG     $774E
PRINT_CTRL_AB:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$81                    ; Ctrl-A with high bit
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDA     #$B0                    ; '0' with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def PRINT_CTRL_AB

\subsection{set\_cursor\_row21 / set\_text\_window\_bottom}
\label{sec:set_text_window}

These two routines share the same code; they differ only in the
window-bottom value loaded in~A.  The BNE at [[$76C0]] forms a
``stretchy branch'' that skips the [[LDA \#\$14]], so both entry points
share all code from [[$76C4]] onward.

<<set text window bottom>>=
    ORG     $76BE
SET_CURSOR_ROW21:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     #$15                    ; WNDBTM = 21
    BNE     .shared                 ; always taken (stretchy branch)

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM:
    LDA     #$14                    ; WNDBTM = 20

.shared:
    STA     TEXT_ROW
    LDA     #$00
    STA     TEXT_COL                ; WNDLFT = 0
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDA     #$86                    ; Ctrl-F with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def SET_CURSOR_ROW21 SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM

\subsection{pos\_to\_colrow (\$0C25)}

Converts a packed map position (0--199) into separate column and row
values by dividing by~20.  The map is 20~columns wide, so
[[column = pos mod 20]] and [[row = pos / 20]].

The loop repeatedly subtracts~20 (via [[ADC \#\$EC]] with carry clear,
since [[\$EC = 256 $-$ 20]]), counting iterations in~[[Y]].  When the
subtraction underflows (carry clear on exit), it adds~20 back to recover
the remainder.

<<pos to colrow>>=
    ORG     $0C25
POS_TO_COLROW:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY      #$00              ; row = 0
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EC              ; A -= 20 (unsigned)
    BCC      .done             ; underflow → remainder is negative
    INY                        ; row++
    BCS      .loop             ; always taken (carry set)
.done:
    ADC      #$14              ; add 20 back → A = column (remainder)
    RTS                        ; A = column (0-19), Y = row (0-9)
@ %def POS_TO_COLROW

\subsection{print\_mob\_name (\$0D8A)}

Loads the name pointer from bytes~0--1 of the mob record at~[[ENTITY\_PTR]]
into~[[\PRINT_STRING_ADDR/\PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]], then tail-calls the text centering routine
at~\$7705, which centers and prints the name on screen row~23.
Used by 13~callers throughout the combat and interaction code.

<<print mob name>>=
    ORG     $0D8A
PRINT_MOB_NAME:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00                    ; \
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y                 ;  | PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1 = bytes 0-1 of ($F8)
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR                     ;  | (name string pointer)
    INY                             ;  |
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y                 ;  |
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1                     ; /
    JMP     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED   ; center and print on row 23
@ %def PRINT_MOB_NAME

\subsection{colrow\_to\_pos (\$0D98)}

The inverse of [[POS\_TO\_COLROW]]: converts a column in~A and row in~Y
to a linear map position [[A = col + row * 20]].  The carry is cleared
once on entry; thereafter the loop adds~20 per row and exits early if
carry occurs (overflow past 255).

<<colrow to pos>>=
    ORG     $0D98
COLROW_TO_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    CLC
.loop:
    DEY                         ; row--
    BPL     .add                ; still >= 0 → add another 20
    RTS                         ; Y exhausted, A = result
.add:
    ADC     #$14                ; A += 20
    BCC     .loop               ; no overflow → continue
                                ; carry set → return (overflow)
@ %def COLROW_TO_POS

\subsection{num\_to\_decimal (\$0DA1)}

Converts a 16-bit unsigned value in~[[NUM\_VALUE]] to up to 5~ASCII
decimal digits, stored sequentially at [[$(DECIMAL\_OUT\_PTR),Y$]] (with Y incrementing).
Leading zeros are suppressed unless the value is exactly zero (prints
``0'').  The output uses Apple~II high-ASCII ($\$B0$--$\$B9$).

The driver at~\$0DA1 calls the digit-extraction helper at~\$0DE1 five
times with divisors 10000, 1000, 100, 10, and~1.  The helper performs
repeated subtraction of [[\$5A1C/\$5A1D]] from [[NUM\_VALUE]], counting
iterations as the digit value.

A second entry point at~[[\$0DA4]] (1~caller) skips the initialization
of~Y and the leading-zero flag, allowing the caller to control the
starting output position and suppression behavior.

<<num to decimal>>=
    ORG     $0DA1
NUM_TO_DECIMAL:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00                    ; output index = 0
    STY     NUM_LEADING             ; leading-zero flag = 0 (suppress)
NUM_TO_DECIMAL_CONT:
    LDA     #$10                    ; \  divisor = $2710 = 10000
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR             ;  |
    LDA     #$27                    ;  |
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR+1           ; /
    JSR     .extract_digit          ; ten-thousands digit
    LDA     #$E8                    ; \  divisor = $03E8 = 1000
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR             ;  |
    LDA     #$03                    ;  |
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR+1           ; /
    JSR     .extract_digit          ; thousands digit
    LDA     #$64                    ; \  divisor = $0064 = 100
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR             ;  |
    LDA     #$00                    ;  |
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR+1           ; /
    JSR     .extract_digit          ; hundreds digit
    LDA     #$0A                    ; \  divisor = $000A = 10
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR             ; /  (high byte already 0)
    JSR     .extract_digit          ; tens digit
    LDA     #$01                    ; \  divisor = $0001 = 1
    STA     NUM_DIVISOR             ;  |
    STA     NUM_LEADING             ; /  force output (no suppress)
    JSR     .extract_digit          ; ones digit
    RTS

; --- Digit extraction helper ($0DE1) ---
; Divides NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 by $5A1C/$5A1D via repeated subtraction.
; Stores ASCII digit at (DECIMAL_OUT_PTR),Y. Suppresses leading zeros.
.extract_digit:
    LDA     #$B0                    ; digit = '0' (high ASCII)
    STA     NUM_DIGIT
.cmp_loop:
    LDX     #$01                    ; start comparing high byte
.cmp_x:
    LDA     NUM_VALUE,X                   ; \
    CMP     NUM_DIVISOR,X           ;  | compare NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 with divisor
    BCC     .output                 ;  | if less, done (digit found)
    BNE     .subtract               ; /  if greater, subtract
    DEX                             ; \  high bytes equal: check low
    BNE     .subtract               ; /  (if X was 1, now 0 -> recompare)
    JMP     .cmp_x                  ;    compare low byte (X=0)
.subtract:
    SEC                             ; \
    LDA     NUM_VALUE                     ;  | NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 -= divisor
    SBC     NUM_DIVISOR             ;  |
    STA     NUM_VALUE                     ;  |
    LDA     NUM_VALUE+1                     ;  |
    SBC     NUM_DIVISOR+1           ;  |
    STA     NUM_VALUE+1                     ; /
    INC     NUM_DIGIT               ; digit++
    JMP     .cmp_loop               ; try again (reset X=1)
.output:
    LDA     NUM_DIGIT               ; \
    CMP     #$B0                    ;  | if digit is '0'
    BNE     .store                  ;  |   and leading-zero suppress active
    LDA     NUM_LEADING             ;  |   skip output
    CMP     #$01                    ;  |
    BNE     .skip                   ; /
    LDA     #$B0                    ; (reload '0' for final digit)
.store:
    STA     (DECIMAL_OUT_PTR),Y                 ; store digit at output buffer
    LDA     #$01                    ; \  clear leading-zero suppress
    STA     NUM_LEADING             ; /  (first nonzero digit seen)
.skip:
    INY                             ; advance output index
    RTS
@ %def NUM_TO_DECIMAL NUM_TO_DECIMAL_CONT

\subsection{check\_encounter (\$0E25)}

Checks whether a given character (by char index in~[[A]]) is co-located
with a mob from an opposing faction.  Calls [[FIND\_ENTITY\_AT\_POS]] to
resolve the character to a mob pointer, then walks the group chain via
[[FIND\_MOB\_AT\_SAME\_POS]] looking for another mob at the same map
position.  Candidate mobs must have byte~6 bits~5--0~$\ge3$ (active mob
type) and be from a different faction (checked via [[CHECK\_HOSTILE]]).

Result stored in [[\$5A1F]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0 --- no mob found at same position (or character is not a mob)
\item 1 --- found co-located mob but same faction (wrapped search)
\item 2 --- found co-located mob from opposing faction (enemy encounter)
\end{itemize}

Callers use the result to set or clear bit~2 of byte~\$0F of the
character's record, which appears to be a ``combat engaged'' flag.

<<defines>>=
ENCOUNTER_RESULT        EQU     $5A1F   ; 0/1/2 from CHECK_ENCOUNTER
@ %def ENCOUNTER_RESULT

<<check encounter>>=
    ORG     $0E25
CHECK_ENCOUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS      ; look up char → ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    CMP     #$00
    BEQ     .none                   ; null pointer → return 0
    CMP     #$80
    BMI     .none                   ; not a mob (bit 7 clear) → return 0
    AND     #$7F                    ; clear mob flag
    STA     MOB_PTR+1                     ; \ MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    LDA     ENTITY_REC                     ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR                     ; /
.search:
    LDA     MOB_PTR                     ; \ TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = current mob pointer
    STA     TARGET_REC                     ;  |
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1                     ;  |
    STA     TARGET_REC+1                     ; /
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS    ; find next mob at same position
    CMP     #$01
    BMI     .none                   ; 0 = no co-located mob → return 0
    BEQ     .friendly               ; 1 = found (wrapped) → return 1
    LDY     #$06                    ; result >= 2: found ahead
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 6 of found mob
    AND     #$3F                    ; bits 5-0
    CMP     #$03                    ; active mob type?
    BCC     .search                 ; no → skip, keep searching
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE           ; compare factions
    CMP     #$00
    BEQ     .search                 ; same faction → skip
    LDA     #$02                    ; enemy found → return 2
    STA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    RTS
.none:
    LDA     #$00
    BEQ     .store
.friendly:
    LDA     #$01
.store:
    STA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_ENCOUNTER

\subsection{find\_mob\_at\_same\_pos (\$0E6C)}

Walks the group chain starting from the current mob ([[MOB\_PTR]]),
looking for another mob at the same map position (byte~3 of mob data).
If the current mob is the last in the chain (byte~2 = 0), the search
wraps around to the first mob via the group head ([[\$FA/\$FB]]).

Returns in~[[A]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0 --- no other mob at same position (full circle)
\item 1 --- found co-located mob (search wrapped past end of chain)
\item 2 --- found co-located mob ahead in the chain
\end{itemize}

On success, [[MOB\_PTR]] is updated to point to the found mob.

<<defines>>=
COLOCATE_POS            EQU     $5A21   ; saved position for co-location search
COLOCATE_LINK           EQU     $5A20   ; saved next-link (stop condition)
COLOCATE_WRAPPED        EQU     $5A22   ; 1 if wrapped, 2 if ahead
@ %def COLOCATE_POS COLOCATE_LINK COLOCATE_WRAPPED

<<find mob at same pos>>=
    ORG     $0E6C
FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 3 = position of current mob
    STA     COLOCATE_POS
    DEY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 2 = next link of current mob
    STA     COLOCATE_LINK
    STY     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; $5A22 = 2 (found ahead)
.check_link:
    CMP     #$00
    BNE     .resolve                ; has next → follow it
    LDY     #$01
    STY     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; wrapped to start
    INY                             ; Y = 2
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y                 ; byte 2 of group head = first mob
.resolve:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA            ; A = mob index → MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y                 ; byte 2 of resolved mob
    CMP     COLOCATE_LINK           ; same next-link as original?
    BNE     .not_self
    LDA     #$00                    ; full circle → not found
    RTS
.not_self:
    INY                             ; Y = 3
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y                 ; byte 3 = position
    CMP     COLOCATE_POS            ; same position as original?
    BEQ     .found
    DEY                             ; Y = 2
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y                 ; follow next link
    JMP     .check_link
.found:
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR                     ; \ update MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 to found mob
    STA     MOB_PTR                     ;  |
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1                     ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR+1                     ; /
    LDA     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; return 1 (wrapped) or 2 (ahead)
    RTS
@ %def FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS

\subsection{check\_hostile (\$0EB1)}

Determines whether two mobs are hostile to each other by comparing their
faction classifications.  Reads byte~4 (appearance index) from the mob
at [[MOB\_PTR]] and the mob at [[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]], converts each via
[[APPEARANCE\_TO\_FONTCHAR]] to get the font group (quotient of dividing
by~21), then classifies via [[GET\_HOSTILITY]]: groups 0--2 and~7 are
``friendly'' (Y=0), groups 3--6 are ``hostile'' (Y=1).

Returns [[A]]=1 if the two mobs are on different sides, [[A]]=0 if same.
When both are hostile (Y=1), they are still hostile to each other if
their font-char remainders differ (different hostile sub-factions).

<<defines>>=
HOSTILE_APP             EQU     $5A23   ; saved appearance for hostility check
HOSTILE_A               EQU     $5A24   ; saved A from first GET_HOSTILITY
HOSTILE_Y               EQU     $5A25   ; saved Y from first GET_HOSTILITY
@ %def HOSTILE_APP HOSTILE_A HOSTILE_Y

<<check hostile>>=
    ORG     $0EB1
CHECK_HOSTILE:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 4 of found mob (appearance)
    STA     HOSTILE_APP
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y                 ; byte 4 of original mob (appearance)
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR  ; → A=remainder, Y=group
    JSR     GET_HOSTILITY           ; → Y=0 (friendly) or 1 (hostile)
    STA     HOSTILE_A
    STY     HOSTILE_Y
    LDA     HOSTILE_APP             ; appearance of found mob
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
    JSR     GET_HOSTILITY
    CPY     HOSTILE_Y               ; compare hostilities
    BNE     .different              ; different sides → hostile
    CPY     #$00
    BEQ     .same                   ; both friendly → same side
    CMP     HOSTILE_A               ; both hostile: compare sub-factions
    BNE     .different              ; different → hostile to each other
.same:
    LDA     #$00
    RTS
.different:
    LDA     #$01
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_HOSTILE

\subsection{get\_hostility (\$0EE3)}

Classifies a font group number (in~[[Y]], from [[APPEARANCE\_TO\_FONTCHAR]])
as friendly or hostile.  Groups 0--2 and~7 are friendly (Y$\leftarrow$0),
groups 3--6 are hostile (Y$\leftarrow$1).  The value in~[[A]] is preserved.

<<get hostility>>=
    ORG     $0EE3
GET_HOSTILITY:
    SUBROUTINE

    CPY     #$03                    ; factions 0-2 = friendly
    BCC     .friendly
    CPY     #$07                    ; faction 7 = friendly
    BEQ     .friendly
    LDY     #$01                    ; factions 3-6 = hostile
    RTS
.friendly:
    LDY     #$00
    RTS
@ %def GET_HOSTILITY

\subsection{check\_adjacent\_threats (\$0EF1)}

Checks the four cardinal neighbors of a map position for hostile mobs
and accumulates their combined threat level.  Input: [[A]]~= position
(0--199), [[ENTITY\_PTR]]~= character record pointer,
[[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]]~= character's mob data pointer.

For each adjacent position (left, right, up, down), calls
[[SUM\_HOSTILE\_AT\_POS]] to find hostile mobs not already in combat and
sum their strength (byte~5 bits~4--0) into [[\$5A26]].  After checking
all neighbors, compares the accumulated threat against the character's
defense value (byte~5 bits~4--1 of the [[ENTITY\_PTR]] record).

Returns [[A]]=1 if defense~$\ge$~threat (safe), [[A]]=0 if overwhelmed.
The threat total remains in [[\$5A26]] for callers that check it directly.

Boundary checks prevent wrapping: position~0 has no left neighbor,
position~199 no right, positions~0--19 no up, positions~180--199 no down.

<<defines>>=
ADJACENT_THREAT         EQU     $5A26   ; accumulated adjacent threat level
ADJACENT_POS            EQU     $5A27   ; saved position for adjacency check
@ %def ADJACENT_THREAT ADJACENT_POS

<<check adjacent threats>>=
    ORG     $0EF1
CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS:
    SUBROUTINE

    STA     ADJACENT_POS            ; save target position
    LDA     #$00
    STA     ADJACENT_THREAT         ; clear threat accumulator
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR                     ; \ TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = character record pointer
    STA     TARGET_REC                     ;  |
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR+1                     ;  |
    STA     TARGET_REC+1                     ; /
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS            ; reload position
    BEQ     .skip_left              ; position 0 → no left neighbor
    SEC
    SBC     #$01                    ; position - 1
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS      ; check left
.skip_left:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    CMP     #$C7                    ; position 199?
    BEQ     .skip_right             ; → no right neighbor
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                    ; position + 1
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS      ; check right
.skip_right:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    BMI     .do_up                  ; >= 128 → always has up neighbor
    CMP     #$14                    ; < 20?
    BMI     .skip_up                ; → no up neighbor
.do_up:
    SEC
    SBC     #$14                    ; position - 20
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS      ; check up
.skip_up:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    BPL     .do_down                ; < 128 → always has down neighbor
    CMP     #$B4                    ; >= 180?
    BPL     .skip_down              ; → no down neighbor
.do_down:
    CLC
    ADC     #$14                    ; position + 20
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS      ; check down
.skip_down:
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y                 ; byte 5 of character record
    ROR                             ; \ bits 4-1 → defense value
    AND     #$0F                    ; /
    CMP     ADJACENT_THREAT         ; compare with threat total
    BPL     .safe                   ; defense >= threat → safe
    LDA     #$00
    RTS                             ; return 0 = overwhelmed
.safe:
    LDA     #$01
    RTS                             ; return 1 = safe
@ %def CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS

\subsection{sum\_hostile\_at\_pos (\$0F49)}

Finds all hostile mobs at a given map position and adds their strength
to the threat accumulator [[\$5A26]].  Input: [[A]]~= position,
[[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]]~= reference mob for faction comparison.

For each mob found at the position, checks hostility via
[[CHECK\_HOSTILE]] and skips mobs that are already combat-engaged
(bit~2 of byte~\$0F set).  Hostile mobs contribute their strength
(byte~5 bits~4--0) to the running total, clamped at~127.

<<sum hostile at pos>>=
    ORG     $0F49
SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS      ; A = position → ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BEQ     .done                   ; null → nothing here
    CMP     #$80
    BMI     .done                   ; not a mob → skip
    AND     #$7F                    ; clear mob flag
    STA     MOB_PTR+1                     ; \ MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    LDA     ENTITY_REC                     ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR                     ; /
.check_mob:
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE           ; is this mob hostile to (TARGET_REC)?
    CMP     #$00
    BEQ     .next                   ; not hostile → skip
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte $0F of mob
    AND     #$04                    ; bit 2 = combat engaged flag
    BNE     .next                   ; already in combat → skip
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y                 ; byte 5 of mob
    AND     #$1F                    ; bits 4-0 = strength
    CLC
    ADC     ADJACENT_THREAT         ; accumulate threat
    BPL     .store
    LDA     #$7F                    ; clamp to 127
.store:
    STA     ADJACENT_THREAT
.next:
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS    ; find next mob at same position
    CMP     #$02
    BEQ     .check_mob              ; more mobs → check them too
.done:
    RTS
@ %def SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS

\subsection{compute\_scene\_ptr (\$0C32)}

Computes a pointer into the game data from a 1-based scene index in~A.
Each scene record is 16 bytes.  The result
[[MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1 = ($4000) + (index - 1) \times 16$]] is stored in [[MOB_DATA_PTR]]/[[MOB_DATA_PTR+1]],
where [[$4000/$4001]] holds the base address of the scene table.

<<compute scene ptr>>=
    ORG     $0C32
COMPUTE_SCENE_PTR:
GET_MOB_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE

    CLC
    ADC     #$FF                    ; A = index - 1
    ROL                       ; \
    ROL                       ;  | rotate left 4 times
    ROL                       ;  | = multiply by 16 (with carry)
    ROL                       ; /
    TAY                             ; save intermediate
    ROL                       ; one more rotate
    AND     #$0F                    ; high nybble → page offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4001                   ; add base page
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1             ; high byte
    TYA
    AND     #$F0                    ; low nybble → byte offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4000                   ; add base offset
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR               ; low byte
    BCC     .done
    INC     MOB_DATA_PTR+1             ; carry
.done:
    RTS
@ %def COMPUTE_SCENE_PTR GET_MOB_DATA

\subsection{appearance\_to\_fontchar (\$0CF7)}

Converts a mob appearance index (byte~4 of mob data) into a font
character number.  The custom font has 120 characters in groups of~32,
but only 21~mob glyphs occupy each group (characters 1--21 and 33--36).
Characters 5--21 repeat cyclically for higher appearance values.

The routine divides the appearance value by~21 (via repeated subtraction
of~21), producing a quotient in~[[Y]] and a 1-based remainder in~[[A]].
If the remainder is~$\ge5$, it is returned directly.  If~$<5$ and the
quotient is nonzero, 32 is added to index into the next font group.

<<appearance to fontchar>>=
    ORG     $0CF7
APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY      #$00              ; Y = quotient (font group)
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EB              ; A -= 21 (unsigned: $EB = 256-21)
    BCC      .done             ; underflow → done dividing
    INY                        ; group++
    BCS      .loop             ; always taken
.done:
    ADC      #$16              ; restore remainder+1 (carry clear, so +22)
    CMP      #$05              ; remainder >= 5?
    BCC      .low              ; no → check group
    RTS                        ; yes → return as-is (chars 5-21)
.low:
    CPY      #$00              ; first group?
    BEQ      .ret              ; yes → return as-is (chars 1-4)
    CLC
    ADC      #$20              ; add 32 → next font group (chars 33-36)
.ret:
    RTS
@ %def APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR

\subsection{delay\_with\_animation (\$0D10)}

Delays for a configurable duration while keeping the status window
animation running.  Loads an iteration count from [[\$7ABF]] and calls
[[\$0D30]] (the per-tick animation/wait handler) that many times.
Each call to [[\$0D30]] ticks an animation counter, runs a timed wait
via the ROM [[WAIT]] routine, and advances the animation frame when
the counter expires.

<<defines>>=
DELAY_COUNT             EQU     $7ABF   ; number of delay iterations
@ %def DELAY_COUNT

<<delay with animation>>=
    ORG     $0D10
DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     DELAY_COUNT             ; load iteration count
.loop:
    PHA                             ; save counter
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT      ; tick animation + timed wait
    PLA                             ; restore counter
    TAY
    DEY                             ; decrement
    TYA
    BNE     .loop                   ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION

\subsection{tick\_anim\_counter (\$0D1E)}

Decrements the animation frame counter at [[\$7AAF]].  When it reaches
zero, calls [[\$74CB]] to advance the animation frame.  Then reloads
the wait loop count from the timing table at [[\$7AB0]] (indexed by
the current animation index at [[\$7ABD]]) into [[\$5A8C]].

<<defines>>=
ANIM_FRAME_CTR          EQU     $7AAF   ; animation frame countdown
ANIM_INDEX              EQU     $7ABD   ; current animation table index
ANIM_WAIT_TABLE         EQU     $7AB0   ; per-frame wait counts (indexed)
ANIM_FRAME_TABLE        EQU     $7AB6   ; per-frame frame counts (indexed)
WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         EQU     $5A8C   ; inner wait loop counter
WAIT_DURATION           EQU     $7AAD   ; ROM WAIT duration parameter
BLINK_DELAY             EQU     $7AAC   ; delay value loaded into WAIT_LOOP_COUNT by DRAW_MAP_ICON_B
MAP_REDRAW_FLAG         EQU     $7AC4   ; non-zero = full map redraw needed
@ %def ANIM_FRAME_CTR ANIM_INDEX ANIM_WAIT_TABLE ANIM_FRAME_TABLE WAIT_LOOP_COUNT WAIT_DURATION BLINK_DELAY MAP_REDRAW_FLAG

<<tick anim counter>>=
    ORG     $0D1E
TICK_ANIM_COUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE

    DEC     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; tick frame counter
    BNE     .reload                 ; not zero → just reload wait count
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_ALT          ; counter hit zero → draw alt char
.reload:
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX              ; current animation index
    LDA     ANIM_WAIT_TABLE,X       ; look up wait count for this frame
    STA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; store for timed_wait to use
    RTS
@ %def TICK_ANIM_COUNTER

\subsection{anim\_tick\_and\_wait (\$0D30)}

Combined animation tick and wait.  Calls [[TICK\_ANIM\_COUNTER]] to
decrement the frame counter and set up the wait count, then calls
[[TIMED\_WAIT]] to burn time.  If the frame counter has reached zero
(meaning the animation frame expired), calls [[\$74DD]] to update the
display and reloads the frame counter from the frame table at
[[\$7AB6]].

<<anim tick and wait>>=
    ORG     $0D30
ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    JSR     TICK_ANIM_COUNTER       ; tick counter, reload wait count
    JSR     TIMED_WAIT              ; burn time
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; did frame counter expire?
    BEQ     .advance                ; yes → advance animation
    RTS                             ; no → return

.advance:
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL       ; redraw blink char in normal video
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX              ; reload animation index
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_TABLE,X      ; look up frame duration
    STA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR          ; reset frame counter
    RTS
@ %def ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT

\subsection{timed\_wait (\$0D49)}

Calls the ROM [[WAIT]] wrapper [[\$0D58]] repeatedly, decrementing
[[WAIT\_LOOP\_COUNT]] until it reaches zero.  If the count is already
zero on entry, returns immediately.

<<timed wait>>=
    ORG     $0D49
TIMED_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; anything to wait for?
    BNE     .wait                   ; yes → enter wait loop
    RTS                             ; no → return immediately

.wait:
    JSR     CALL_ROM_WAIT           ; delay one unit
    DEC     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         ; decrement counter
    BNE     .wait                   ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def TIMED_WAIT

\subsection{call\_rom\_wait (\$0D58)}

Loads the wait duration from [[WAIT\_DURATION]] and jumps to the
Apple~II ROM [[WAIT]] routine at [[\$FCA8]], which delays for
approximately $A \times 2.5 + 13.5$ microseconds.

<<defines>>=
ROM_WAIT                EQU     $FCA8   ; Apple II ROM WAIT routine
@ %def ROM_WAIT

<<call rom wait>>=
    ORG     $0D58
CALL_ROM_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDA     WAIT_DURATION           ; load duration parameter
    JMP     ROM_WAIT                ; tail-call ROM WAIT
@ %def CALL_ROM_WAIT

\section{Text renderer}
\label{sec:text_renderer}

Reads a byte stream from the pointer at [[$06/$07]] and renders
characters on the hi-res screen.  It maintains column/row state and
supports several control codes.

<<defines>>=
TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN        EQU     $5A96   ; right margin column for text wrap
TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         EQU     $5A97   ; left margin column for text wrap
TEXT_STREAM_IDX          EQU     $5A98   ; saved Y index into byte stream
@ %def TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN TEXT_STREAM_IDX

<<text renderer>>=
    ORG     $6C8E
TEXT_RENDERER:
    SUBROUTINE

    LDY     #$00
.init:
    LDA     #$02
    STA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         ; left margin = 2
    STA     FONT_COL                ; current column = 2
    LDA     #$12
    STA     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; right margin = $12 (18)
    LDA     #$01
    STA     FONT_ROW                ; current row = 1

    ; --- Main byte-reading loop ---
.fetch:
    LDA     (TEXT_STREAM_PTR),Y     ; read byte from stream
    BMI     .set_pos                ; bit 7 set → position command
    CMP     #$7F
    BNE     .not_end
    RTS                             ; $7F = end of stream

.not_end:
    CMP     #$7E
    BEQ     .pause                  ; $7E = pause
    CMP     #$7D
    BEQ     .reset                  ; $7D = reset to full-screen mode

    ; --- Character output ---
    STY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX                   ; save stream index
    STA     FONT_CHARNUM            ; character code
    LDA     #$02
    STA     FONT_CHARSET            ; character width = 2
    JSR     PRINT_FONTCHAR          ; draw at current position
    INC     FONT_COL                ; advance column
    LDA     FONT_COL
    CMP     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; past right margin?
    BCC     .next                   ; no → continue
    INC     FONT_ROW                ; yes → next row
    LDA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN        ;   reset column to left margin
    STA     FONT_COL
.next:
    LDY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX                   ; restore stream index
    INY                             ; advance to next byte
    BNE     .fetch                  ; loop (max 256 per page)
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP               ; overflow handler

    ; --- Position command ($80-$FE) ---
.set_pos:
    AND     #$7F                    ; row = byte & $7F
    STA     FONT_ROW
    INY
    LDA     (TEXT_STREAM_PTR),Y     ; next byte = column
    STA     FONT_COL
    INY
    JMP     .fetch

    ; --- Pause ($7E): run script engine, show status bar ---
.pause:
    TYA                             ; \
    PHA                             ;  | save stream index
    NOP
    LDX     #$06
    JSR     SCRIPT_ENGINE           ; run attract script
    PSHW    TEXT_STREAM_PTR         ; save stream pointer
    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR      ; (clobbers TEXT_STREAM_PTR)
    PULW    TEXT_STREAM_PTR         ; restore stream pointer
    PLA                             ; restore stream index
    TAY
    NOP
    INY                             ; advance past $7E
    JMP     .init                   ; reinit margins/position

    ; --- Reset ($7D): full-screen text mode ---
.reset:
    LDA     #$00
    STA     TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         ; left margin = 0
    STA     FONT_COL                ; column = 0
    STA     FONT_ROW                ; row = 0
    LDA     #$14
    STA     TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN       ; right margin = $14 (20)
    INY                             ; advance past $7D
    JMP     .fetch
@ %def TEXT_RENDERER
@

\subsection{Control code summary}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cl}
\toprule
\thead{Byte} & \thead{Meaning} \\
\midrule
\$7D & Reset to full-screen mode (col=0, row=0, width=20) \\
\$7E & Pause: run script engine and status bar, then resume \\
\$7F & End of stream \\
\$80--\$FE & Set row (byte \& \$7F), next byte = column \\
Other & Character code for HRCG font \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

